Grading the professor

Many college courses conclude by giving students the opportunity to evaluate the course and the instructor anonymously. However, the use of these student evaluations as an indicator of course quality and teaching effectiveness is often criticized because these measures may reflect the influence of non-teaching related characteristics, such as the physical appearance of the instructor. The article titled, Beauty in the classroom: instructors pulchritude and putative pedagogical productivity (Hamermesh and Parker 2005) found that instructors who are judged more attractive receive higher instructional ratings.

In this lab, we will analyze the data from this study in order to learn what goes into a positive professor evaluation.

Getting Started

Load packages

In this lab, the dplyr package by Wickham and Francois (2016) is used to explore the data. Visualization of the data is accomplished with the ggplot2 and GGally packages created by Wickham and Chang (2016) and Schloerke et al. (2016), respectively. The data resides in the statsr package created by Rundel et al. (2016). Tables are formatted for html with the htmlTable package created by Gordon (2016) and data is formatted for easy viewing with the DT package by Xie (2015).

Let us load the packages.

library(statsr)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(GGally)
library(htmlTable)
library(DT)

This is the first time we have used the GGally package. We will use the ggpairs function from GGally later in the lab.

The data

The data were gathered from end of semester student evaluations for a large sample of professors from the University of Texas at Austin. In addition, six students rated the professors physical appearance. (This is a slightly modified version of the original data set that was released as part of the replication data for Data Analysis Using Regression and Multilevel/Hierarchical Models (Gelman and Hill 2007).) The result is a data frame where each row contains a different course and columns represent variables about the courses and professors.

Lets load the data:

data(evals)

ggplot(data = evals, aes(x = bty_avg, y = score)) +

Multiple linear regression

The data set contains several variables on the beauty score of the professor as well as individual ratings from each of the six students who were asked to score the physical appearance of the professors. It also has a variable that is the average of these six scores. Let us examine the strength of the linear relationship between one of these scores (bty_f1lower) and the average beauty score (bty_avg).

ggplot(data = evals, aes(x = bty_f1lower, y = bty_avg)) +
  geom_jitter()

# Correlation using cor()
# 1. Just the function
cor(evals$bty_avg, evals$bty_f1lower)
[1] 0.8439112
# 2. Using with() to access the data
with(data = evals, cor(bty_avg, bty_f1lower))
[1] 0.8439112
# 3. using a pipe
evals %>% 
  summarize(r = cor(bty_avg, bty_f1lower))
Source: local data frame [1 x 1]

          r
      <dbl>
1 0.8439112

As expected, the relationship is quite strongafter all, the average score is calculated using the individual scores. Figure 2 depicts the relationships between all beauty variables (columns 13 through 19) using the following command:

# Note: This is a painfully slow function!
ggpairs(evals, columns = 13:19)

Figure 2: GGpairs matrix scatterplot

The variables in Figure 2 are collinear (correlated), and adding more than one of these variables to the model would not add much value to the model. In this application and with these highly-correlated predictors, it is reasonable to use the average beauty score as the single representative of these variables.

In order to see if beauty is still a significant predictor of professor score after we have accounted for the gender of the professor, we can add the gender term into the model.

m_bty_gen <- lm(score ~ bty_avg + gender, data = evals)
summary(m_bty_gen)

Note that the estimate for gender is now called gendermale. The original variable name will change whenever you introduce a categorical variable. The reason the name changes is because R re-codes gender from having values female and male to an indicator variable called gendermale that takes a value of \(0\) for females and a value of \(1\) for males. (Such variables are often referred to as dummy variables.)

As a result, for females, the parameter estimate is multiplied by zero, leaving the intercept and slope form familiar from simple regression.

\[ \begin{aligned} \widehat{\text{score}} &= \hat{\beta}_0 + \hat{\beta}_1 \times \text{bty_avg} + \hat{\beta}_2 \times (0) \\ &= \hat{\beta}_0 + \hat{\beta}_1 \times \text{bty_avg}\end{aligned} \]

  1. For two professors (one male and one female) who received the same beauty rating, the male professor is predicted to have the higher course evaluation score than the female.
    1. True
    2. False

your answer here

The decision to call the indicator variable gendermale instead ofgenderfemale has no deeper meaning. R simply codes the category that comes first alphabetically as a \(0\). (You can change the reference level of a categorical variable, which is the level that is coded as a 0, using therelevel function; use ?relevel to learn more.)

The interpretation of the coefficients in multiple regression is slightly different from that of simple regression. The estimate for bty_avg reflects how much higher a group of professors is expected to score if they have a beauty rating that is one point higher while holding all other variables constant. In this case, that translates into considering only professors of the same rank with bty_avg scores that are one point apart.

Prediction

Suppose we want to use the model we created earlier, m_bty_gen, to predict the evaluation score for a professor, Dr.Hypo Thetical, who is a male tenure track professor with an average beauty score of 3.

If we wanted to do this by hand, we would plug in these values using the fitted linear model.

To compute the predicted value in R, create a new data frame for this professor.

newprof <- data.frame(gender = "male", bty_avg = 3)

Note that I did not need to add rank = "tenure track" to this data frame since this variable is not used in our model.

Then, I can do the prediction using the predict function:

predict(m_bty_gen, newdata = newprof)
       1 
4.142194

We can also construct a prediction interval around this prediction, which will provide a measure of uncertainty around the prediction.

PI <- predict(m_bty_gen, newdata = newprof, interval = "prediction", level = 0.95)
PI
       fit      lwr      upr
1 4.142194 3.100559 5.183829

The model predicts, with 95% confidence, that a male professor with an average beauty score of 3 is expected to have an evaluation score between 3.1006 and 5.1838.

The search for the best model

We will start with a full model that predicts professor score based on rank, ethnicity, gender, language of the university where they got their degree, age, proportion of students that filled out evaluations, class size, course level, number of professors, number of credits, average beauty rating, outfit, and picture color.

Which variable would you expect to have the highest p-value in this model? Why? Hint: Think about which variable would you expect to not have any association with the professor score.

Lets run the model

             + pic_outfit + pic_color, data = evals)
